         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne ¶ 18/9/73. ¶  ¶ Let me thank you, dear Dr Hector, for the kind reception of the list of Algae, also for the sending of the two Restiaceae. ¶ M had requested the Restiaceae in M to J. Hector,...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">73.09.18</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To James Hector</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">Folder 4, box 59, James Hector, correspondence received, Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa Archives, Wellington.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Melbourne</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">18/9/73.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Let me thank you, dear Dr Hector, for the kind reception of the list of Algae, also for the sending of the two Restiaceae.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn0" n="1">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M had requested the Restiaceae in M to J. Hector, 2 August 1873.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>If you could<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">soon</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>procure for me<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont">♂</seg>&amp;<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont">♀</seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>of the two additional species, of the existence of which I was not aware, you would add important material to my supplemental essay on the Australian members of the order,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn1" n="2">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B73.08.01,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>pp.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>64-101, including the description of<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Lepyrodia traversi</seg>.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>which essay must be soon brought to a conclusion for the 7th vol. of the Australian Flora.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn2" n="3">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham (1863-78), vol. 7, pp. 208-46.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>The new Restiacea<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>from Chatham Island (Lepyrodia Traversi) might easily be procured, if letters were written to a few officials or settlers there &amp; fragments for recognizing the plant were sent to them. Indeed other Restiaceae would likely turn up there, though perhaps not so conspicuous as Lepyrodia Traversi. Please ask them to collect these.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Our friend Dr Hooker is so much now engaged on the "genera" of Central African &amp; Indian plants, that he gladly now leaves the N.Z. field to us here in the South.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">your regardful</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Let ripe fruits be with the Restiaceae; if not fresh ones are on the plant, old ones can<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">always</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>be found, if carefully searched for.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Lepyrodia Traversi</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Restiaceae</p>
         </div>
